.TH YQ 1 "2024" "yq 4.35" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
yq \- Command-line YAML processor
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B yq
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fIEXPRESSION\fR [\fIFILE\fR...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B yq
is a lightweight and portable command-line YAML processor. It uses jq-like
syntax but works with YAML files instead of JSON.
.PP
yq can read YAML, JSON, XML, CSV, and TOML files and output to any of these
formats. It supports complex expressions for filtering and transforming data.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-p, \-\-input\-format
Input format: yaml, json, xml, csv, toml (default: yaml)
.TP
.B \-o, \-\-output\-format
Output format: yaml, json, xml, csv, toml (default: yaml)
.TP
.B \-P, \-\-prettyPrint
Pretty print output
.TP
.B \-i, \-\-inplace
Edit file in place
.TP
.B \-e, \-\-exit\-status
Set exit status based on output
.TP
.B \-N, \-\-no\-colors
Disable colored output
.SH BASIC EXPRESSIONS
.TP
.B .
Identity - outputs input unchanged
.TP
.B .foo
Select field "foo"
.TP
.B .[]
Iterate over array/object values
.TP
.B .[0]
Select first array element
.TP
.B keys
Get keys as array
.TP
.B length
Get length of value
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Read a YAML field:
.RS
echo 'name: yq' | yq '.name'
.RE
.PP
Convert YAML to JSON:
.RS
echo 'name: yq' | yq -o json '.'
.RE
.PP
Modify a field:
.RS
echo 'name: old' | yq '.name = "new"'
.RE
